default3default.default0default              defaultUniversal credit Implicationsdefault&#xa0;default3
default.1
default              
defaultA review of the Business Plans for the Council hostels has been undertaken and approved. There are some significant budgetary implications if the current definition of exempt accommodation remains. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultCurrent gross 
defaultoccupation charges are around the £200 per week level. Upon migration to UC the LHA level plus an unknown management fee will be claimable in subsidy. For all but the households with an assessed 4 bed need, the rent level that can be achieved is markedly b
defaultelow the £200 level. The following budget losses have been calculated and approved internally (these losses anticipate a management fee of (£40 per week).
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultThe projected total budget loss of £183,923 compares to a total budget of £127,420 for out of office hours security; or £105,228 hostel staff budget (Supporting People staff budget is separate); or capital repayment 
defaultcosts of nearly £158,000. As you can see, none of these budget areas can fully cover the projected budget loss. None of those budget areas could be tampered with without making the hostel unviable.
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultThe above losses relate to the HRA hostels not being 
defaultexempt accommodation. In addition, rent award will be paid to claimants. Award may be paid to landlord after 4 weeks arrears and will after 8 weeks arrears. Although more difficult to project, budget losses could easily amount to a further £100,000. 
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultGosport Council’s temporary accommodation strategy places high importance to the Councils role in managing statutory homeless
default. One response to the changes upon migration to UC would be to try to get a housing association etcetera to take over the hostels. 
defaultEven if that were possible it would be an unwelcome forced change. That change also appears to be in opposition to the Governments strategy of enabling council’s (through HRA reform) to meet the challenges faced by them.  
